{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411393"},"attributes":{"position":8,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11560"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473894"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11560"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11560"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.1,0.05,0.19,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46190"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4189"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1515"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46190"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-week-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents with a three-day history of loose stools tinged with blood. During this time she has vomited twice, both times immediately after feeding. She is exclusively breastfed. There are no other concerns reported by her parents. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her weight and length are tracking along the 50th percentile. Abdominal examination reveals a soft abdomen with no masses. There are no other significant findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further investigation","Routine blood tests including ESR","Skin prick allergy testing","Serum immunoglobulin E (IgE) antibody levels","Stool microscopy, culture and sensitivity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn view of the presenting symptoms and normal examination, the most probable diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Efood protein-induced allergic proctocolitis (FPIAP)\u003C/strong\u003E. With the limited information provided, the most likely causative agent is cow\u0027s milk protein, sourced from the mother\u0027s diet and reaching the child via the mother\u0027s breastmilk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECompletely eliminating all dairy from the mother\u0027s diet typically resolves the child\u0027s symptoms within a 48-72 hour period. In accordance with the recommendations set out by the Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA), FPIAP is a clinical diagnosis that requires \u003Cstrong\u003Eno formal investigations\u003C/strong\u003E. Rather the best \u201cdiagnostic test\u201d for FPIAP is a positive response to management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoutine blood tests including ESR\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as the diagnosis can be made clinically and the child appears otherwise well. There are no signs or symptoms to suggest an underlying inflammatory process that would warrant checking inflammatory markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EASCIA reports that allergy testing, whether by \u003Cstrong\u003Eskin prick testing\u003C/strong\u003E or measuring \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum IgE levels\u003C/strong\u003E, is negative in infants with FPIAP and is therefore not useful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile bloody diarrhoea can be concerning for infection, the clinical picture is most consistent with FPIAP. Unless the child becomes more unwell or fails to respond to management, \u003Cstrong\u003Estool microscopy, culture and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Food protein-induced allergic proctocolitis (FPIAP) is a clinical diagnosis that requires no formal investigations. The best \u201cdiagnostic test\u201d for FPIAP is a positive response to management."],"references":["Food Protein-Induced Allergic Proctocolitis (FPIAP) [Internet]. Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA); 2019 [cited 12 July 2022]. Available from: https://www.allergy.org.au/images/pcc/ASCIA_PCC_Allergic_Proctocolitis_2019.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11560"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-30T19:46:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-30T19:47:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4189"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46190"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"